<TITLE> Dhaka breathes after weeks of gridlock </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sep 20 (bdnews24.com)Long suffering Dhaka residents, who remained in the city on Sunday, have enjoyed a respite from suffocating gridlock that has become such an unwelcome feature of the capital in the lead up to Eid-ul-Fitr. Bumper-to-bumper traffic, frustrating waits at traffic signals and bustling queues for public transport have now been replaced with wide open avenues in certain sections of the capital. The drastic change, however, sometimes only serves to remind one of what should be the case all year round. "The capital has really emptied, with few traffic jams or ear-splitting horns to contend with on the roads. If it would only last..." Amirul Islam, a resident of Mirpur-10, told bdnews24.com. Islam said he reached the New Market area in only 20 minutes from his home, where it had taken up to an hour-and-a-half in recent days and weeks. Syedul Islam Talat, a bdnews24.com correspondent, said he reached the High Court area from Mirpur Shewrapara in only 17 minutes, an unthinkable feat only a day before. "Usually it takes more than an hour to come to the High Court from Mirpur Shewrapara; the capital has completely emptied ahead of the Eid festival," said Talat. "Comparatively few vehicles are on the roads, although a good number of rickshaws are still plying the back streets," he said. b
